<refentry id="MGR-FAILOVERGTM">
  <refmeta>
    <refentrytitle>FAILOVER GTMCOOR</refentrytitle>
    <manvolnum>7</manvolnum>
    <refmiscinfo>Manage - Language Statements</refmiscinfo>
  </refmeta>

  <refnamediv>
    <refname>FAILOVER GTMCOOR</refname>
    <refpurpose>promote gtmcoor slave to gtmcoor master</refpurpose>
  </refnamediv>

  <indexterm zone="mgr-failovergtm">
    <primary>FAILOVER GTMCOOR</primary>
  </indexterm>

  <refsynopsisdiv>
<synopsis>
FAILOVER GTMCOOR <replaceable class="parameter">node_name</replaceable> [ FORCE ]
</synopsis>
  </refsynopsisdiv>
  <refsect1>
    <title>Description</title>

    <para>
   <command>FAILOVER GTMCOOR</command> promote gtmcoor slave to gtmcoor master, which is synchronized;
     If the gtmcoor slave is not synchronized, and want to promote it to gtmcoor master, use "force" at command end; For the command "failover gtmcoor", it choose the synchronized and running normal slave as the target slave node, which will be promote to gtmcoor master.
    </para>
  </refsect1>
  <refsect1>
    <title>Parameters</title>

  <variablelist>
   <varlistentry>
    <term><replaceable class="parameter">node_name</replaceable></term>
    <listitem>
     <para>
      The gtmcoor master name.
     </para>
    </listitem>
   </varlistentry>
    
  </variablelist>
  </refsect1>
  <refsect1>
    <title>Examples</title>

<para>
Promote one gtmcoor slave to master, which must be synchronized:
<programlisting>
FAILOVER GTMCOOR gtm_mastername;
</programlisting>
 </para>
<para>
promote one gtmcoor slave to master, no matter it is synchronized or not:
<programlisting>
FAILOVER GTMCOOR gtm_mastername FORCE;
</programlisting>
  </para>
  </refsect1>
